\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Functional Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Michael Nelson
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset toc
LatexCommand tableofcontents

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Class Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

th 
\series bold
moment 
\series default
is by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Ij$
\end_inset

 is a subinterval of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The moment problem says that if we are given a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 of real numbers, can we find a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\int_{I}t^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu(t).
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,1]$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hausdorff moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=[0,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Stieltjes moment problem.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $I=(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then this is called the Hamburger moment problem.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let us start with some intuition on how we can solve this problem.
 For a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, let us denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\langle f,\mu\rangle=\int_{I}f\mathrm{d}\mu\label{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In some sense, 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:innerproductfunctionmeasure})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 behaves like an inner-product.
 Of course, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 are different types of mathematical objects; one is a function and the
 other is a measure.
 So for all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convex Cones
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 A set 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 is said to be a 
\series bold
convex cone 
\series default
if
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in K$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in K$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\geq0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given a convex cone 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

, if we have the additional axiom 
\begin_inset Formula $-K\cap K=\{0\}$
\end_inset

, then we can define a partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq_{K}y$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $y-x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 In this case, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq_{K}x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 Thus it makes sense to call the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
positive 
\series default
elements with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\leq_{K}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extending Linear Functionals Which Satisfy Positivity Condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Marcel Extension Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $W\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex cone.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $V=W+K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K\cap W$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 is a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

 and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in K$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V\backslash W$
\end_inset

.
 We will first show that we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W+\mathbb{R}v=\{w+\lambda v\mid w\in W\text{ and }\lambda\in\mathbb{R}\}.
\]

\end_inset

Define two sets
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x\in W\mid x+v\in K\}\quad\text{and}\quad B=\{y\in W\mid y-v\in K\}.
\]

\end_inset

We claim that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}\leq\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}.\label{eq:convexconeineq-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Indeed, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+y & =(x+v)+(y-v)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows us that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\in K$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\psi(x+y)\\
 & =\psi(x)+\psi(y)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $-\psi(x)\leq\psi(y)$
\end_inset

, and hence we have 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:convexconeineq-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(v)$
\end_inset

 to be any number between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{-\psi(x)\mid x\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\psi(y)\mid y\in B\}$
\end_inset

 and we define we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v)=\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\label{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in W+\mathbb{R}v$
\end_inset

.
 Note that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is well-defined since 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 is linearly independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to check that 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:welldefinedpsitilde-1-1-1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 gives us a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon W+\mathbb{R}v\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{W}=\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Furthermore we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\psi(x)\leq\widetilde{\psi}(v)\leq\psi(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in B$
\end_inset

.
 The only thing left is to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}$
\end_inset

 satisfies the positivity condition.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $w+\lambda v\in K\cap(W+\mathbb{R}v)$
\end_inset

.
 We consider the folloiwng cases:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 1: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(1/\lambda)w+v=(1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in K
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\lambda)w\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\lambda(\psi((1/\lambda)w)+\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\series bold
Case 2: 
\series default
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda<0$
\end_inset

.
 Then note that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-1/\lambda)w-v=(-1/\lambda)(w+\lambda v)\in K
\]

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1/\lambda)w\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq-\lambda(\psi((-1/\lambda)w)-\widetilde{\psi}(v))\\
 & =\psi(w)+\lambda\widetilde{\psi}(v)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w+\lambda v).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case 3: 
\series default
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in K\cap W$
\end_inset

, and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\psi(w)\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(w).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the positivity condition is satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 to all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we must appeal to Zorn's Lemma.
 More specifically, we define a partially ordered set 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 as follows: the underlying set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{F}=\{\text{linear functionals }\psi'\colon W'\to\mathbb{R}\mid W'\supseteq W,\text{ }\psi'|_{W}=\psi\text{, and }\psi'(x)\geq0\text{ for all }x\in W'\cap K\}.
\]

\end_inset

A member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 is denoted by an ordered pair: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 are two members of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi_{1},W_{1})\leq(\psi_{2},W_{2})$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{2}\supseteq W_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}|_{W_{1}}=\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that every totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

 has an upper bound.
 Indeed, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a totally ordered subset in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 Then if we set 
\begin_inset Formula $W'=\bigcup_{i\in I}W_{i}$
\end_inset

 and if we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'\colon W\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 as follows: if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in W_{i}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and we set 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi'(x)=\psi_{i}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\psi',W')$
\end_inset

 is a member of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 which is an upper bound of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\psi_{i},W_{i})\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore by Zorn's Lemma, there exists a 
\emph on
maximal 
\emph default
element in 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{F},\leq)$
\end_inset

.
 This maximal element 
\emph on
must 
\emph default
be defined on all of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, otherwise we can extend it to a larger subspace as shown above.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hausdorff Moment Problem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=P[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{\text{nonnegative continuous functions on }[0,1]\}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 we write it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=b_{n}x^{n}+b_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}x+b_{0},
\]

\end_inset

and we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(p)=b_{n}a_{n}+b_{n-1}a_{n-1}+\cdots+b_{1}a_{1}+b_{0}a_{0}.
\]

\end_inset

Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i})=a_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 This is clearly a linear functional on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 The first crucial step is to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We'll need to use the following theorem of Bernstein:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (S.
 Bernstein) A polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is non-negative on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 if and only if it can be represented as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x)=A_{0}x^{n}+A_{1}x^{n-1}(1-x)+A_{2}x^{n-2}(1-x)^{2}+\cdots+A_{n-1}x(1-x)^{n-1}+A_{n}(1-x)^{n}
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{0},A_{1},\dots,A_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j})\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

 then by the previous theorem of Bernstein, we will have 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(p)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out that this is a sufficient condition too.
 We write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{i}(1-x)^{j}=x^{i}\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{k}=\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}x^{i+k}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(x^{i}(1-x)^{j}) & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}\psi(x^{i+k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So we need to impose the condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{k=0}^{j}{j \choose k}(-1)^{k}a_{i+k}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Under this condition, we have that all conditions of the Marcel Riesz extension
 theorem are satisfied, namely we need to check that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{P}+\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 However this is clear: if 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bounded, say 
\begin_inset Formula $f\leq M$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-M)+M,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-M\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So applying the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathcal{M}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(p)=\psi(p)$
\end_inset

 for any polynomial 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 The final important ingredient is the Riesz Representation Theorem:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Riesz Representation Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{lemma}
\backslash
label{lemmadinnistheorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Dini's Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n}\colon X\to\mathbb{R})$
\end_inset

 be an increasing sequence of continuous functions which converges pointwise
 to a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{lemma}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, let 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}=f-f_{n}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}=\{g_{n}<\varepsilon\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and thus each 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{n}$
\end_inset

 is open.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is increasing, each 
\begin_inset Formula $(g_{n})$
\end_inset

 is decreasing, and thus the sequence of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, it follows that the collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 forms an open cover of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 By compactness of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, we can choose a finite subcover of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{E_{n}\}$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 is ascending, this means that there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{N}=X$
\end_inset

.
 Choosing such an 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq N$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varepsilon & >g_{n}(x)\\
 & =f(x)-f_{n}(x)\\
 & =|f(x)-f_{n}(x)|
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) For any linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique finite (positive) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Uniqueness is clear.
 Let's prove existence.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B[0,1]$
\end_inset

 be the space of all bounded functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=B[0,1]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=C[0,1]$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{\text{nonnegative bounded functions}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone.
 We also have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}=\mathcal{P}+\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 by the same reason as before.
 Indeed, for any bounded function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 there exists a continuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\leq f$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=(f-g)+g
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f-g\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 We also know 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{P}\cap\mathcal{N}$
\end_inset

.
 So by the Marcel Riesz extension theorem, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\colon B[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{C[0,1]}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{P}}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Now we define a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu(E)=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{E})
\]

\end_inset

for each 
\begin_inset Formula $E\in\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We next show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a measure.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(E_{n})$
\end_inset

 be a sequence of pairwise disjoint sets in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Observe
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}-f,f-f_{n}\leq|f_{n}-f|\leq\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}
\]

\end_inset

 By the positivity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f),\widetilde{\ell}(f-f_{n})\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}).
\]

\end_inset

Equivalently,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n}-f)|\leq\widetilde{\ell}(\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}})=\|f_{n}-f\|_{\mathrm{sup}}\widetilde{\ell}(1).
\]

\end_inset

Therefore if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 is continuous with respect to the sup norm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is an increasing sequence which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 uniformly (Dini's Theorem).
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{n})$
\end_inset

 is increasing and converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}})$
\end_inset

 is increasing and converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}\right) & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{\infty}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(1_{\bigcup_{n=1}^{N}E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{n=1}^{N}1_{E_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\widetilde{\ell}(E_{n})\\
 & =\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}\mu(E_{n})\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\mu(E_{n}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is a Borel measure on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 It is finite since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu([0,1])=\widetilde{\ell}(1_{[0,1]})<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an increasing sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n})$
\end_inset

 of simple functions which converges pointwise to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then by MCT we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi\mathrm{d}\mu & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\mu(A_{k})\\
 & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}\widetilde{\ell}(1_{A_{k}})\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}\left(\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{k}1_{A_{k}}\right)\\
 & =\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\ell(f)$
\end_inset

.
 We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\ell(f)
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(f)=\int f\mathrm{d}\mu$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 continuous.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another formulation of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Riesz Representation Theorem) For any bounded (with respect to the supremum
 norm) linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(f)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\geq0$
\end_inset

, there exists a unique finite (signed) measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And a more general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem is given
 by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Kakutani general version of the Riesz Representation Theorem) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a compact Hausdorff topological space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 be the Banach space of all continuous functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f\colon X\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 equipped with the supremum norm:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\|f\|_{\infty}=\sup_{x\in X}|f(x)|.
\]

\end_inset

For any bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon C(X)\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique Borel regular measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(f)=\int_{X}f\mathrm{d}\mu.
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly continuous.
 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 define a partition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0<x_{0}^{(n)}<x_{1}^{(n)}<\cdots<x_{n}^{(n)}=1
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that none of these points are discontinuities of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
|x_{i+1}^{(n)}-x_{i}^{(n)}|<\frac{2}{n}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1,\dots,n$
\end_inset

.
 Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{n}\colon[0,1]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{n}(x)=\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is uniformly continuous, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\varphi_{n})$
\end_inset

 converges uniformly to 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n})\to\widetilde{\ell}(f)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu\to\int_{0}^{1}f\mathrm{d}\mu$
\end_inset

.
 So it suffices to show
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu=\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n}).
\]

\end_inset

Thus
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\ell}(\varphi_{n}) & =\widetilde{\ell}(\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]})\\
 & =\sum_{i=0}^{n-1}f(x_{i}^{(n)})\widetilde{\ell}(1_{(x_{i}^{(n)},x_{i+1}^{(n)}]})\\
 & =\int_{0}^{1}\varphi_{n}\mathrm{d}\mu
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Hausdorff) A sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $(a_{n})$
\end_inset

 is a moment sequence of some finite Borel measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}x^{n}\mathrm{d}\mu
\]

\end_inset

if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $(-1)^{k}(\Delta^{k}a)_{n}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k,n\geq0$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Delta a)_{n}=a_{n+1}-a_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Delta^{2}a & =\Delta(\Delta a)\\
 & =(a_{n+2}-2a_{n+1}+a_{n})_{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

More generally
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta^{k}a=(\sum_{i=n}^{n+k}(-1)^{i}{n \choose i}a_{n+i}).
\]

\end_inset

Sequences satisfying this condition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((-1)^{k}\Delta^{k}a)_{n}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

are called monotone sequences.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-1)^{k}(\Delta^{k}a)_{n}=\int_{0}^{1}x^{n}(1-x)^{k}\mathrm{d}\mu\geq0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hahn-Banach Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space.
 A 
\series bold
partial-seminorm 
\series default
is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(nonnegativity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\geq0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(nonnegative homogeneity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\lambda x)=\lambda p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x+y)\leq p(x)+p(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The terminology 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial-seminorm
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is made up by me.
 Recall that a 
\series bold
seminorm 
\series default
is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 which satisfies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(absolute homogeneity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(\lambda x)=|\lambda|p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
(subadditivity) 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x+y)\leq p(x)+p(y)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easy to check that a seminorm is necessarily nonnegative.
 Thus every seminorm is a partial-seminorm.
 On the other hand, there are partial-seminorms which are not seminorms.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space equipped with a partial-seminorm 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 be a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 Then every linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}|_{U}=\varphi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\widetilde{\varphi}|\leq p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that by 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

, we mean 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi(u)|\leq p(u)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a linear functional such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|\varphi|\leq p|_{U}$
\end_inset

.
 We will construct an extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 using Marcel Riesz's Extension Theorem.
 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\{(\lambda,v)\in\mathbb{R}\times V\mid p(v)\leq\lambda\}.
\]

\end_inset

Then observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is a convex cone contained in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times V$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\alpha\lambda,\alpha v)\in P$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(\alpha v) & =\alpha p(v)\\
 & \leq\alpha\lambda
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Also if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{1},v_{1}),(\lambda_{2},v_{2})\in P$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2},v_{1}+v_{2})\in P$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p(v_{1}+v_{2}) & \leq p(v_{1})+p(v_{2})\\
 & =\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Furthermore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\times V=(\mathbb{R}\times U)+P$
\end_inset

 , since if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in\mathbb{R}\times V$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\lambda,v)=(\lambda-p(v),0)+(p(v),v)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda-p(v),0)\in\mathbb{R}\times U$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(p(v),v)\in P$
\end_inset

.
 Finally define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathbb{R}\times U\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(\lambda,u)=\lambda-\varphi(u)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,u)\in\mathbb{R}\times U$
\end_inset

.
 Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi|_{(\mathbb{R}\times U)\cap P}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,v)\in(\mathbb{R}\times U)\cap P$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\psi(\lambda,v) & =\lambda-\varphi(v)\\
 & \geq\lambda-p(v)\\
 & \geq0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus we have all of the ingredients to apply the Marcel Riesz Extension
 Theorem: choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}\colon\mathbb{R}\times V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{\mathbb{R}\times U}=\psi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\psi}|_{P}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}(v)=-\widetilde{\psi}(0,v)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\widetilde{\varphi}(u) & =-\widetilde{\psi}(0,u)\\
 & =-\psi(0,u)\\
 & =\varphi(u).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\varphi}|_{U}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 We claim 
\begin_inset Formula $|\widetilde{\varphi}|\leq p$
\end_inset

.
 To see this, assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\varphi}(v_{0})>p(v_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then using that 
\begin_inset Formula $(p(x_{0}),x_{0})\in P$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & \leq\widetilde{\psi}(p(x_{0}),x_{0})\\
 & =\widetilde{\psi}(0,x_{0})+\widetilde{\psi}(p(x_{0}),0)\\
 & =-\widetilde{\varphi}(x_{0})+\psi(p(x_{0}),0)\\
 & =-\widetilde{\varphi}(x_{0})+p(x_{0})\\
 & <-p(x_{0})+p(x_{0})\\
 & =0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is a contradiction.
 This establishes our claim and we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In the setting of normed linear spaces, the Hahn-Banach Theorem says that
 any linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 defined on a subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 which is bounded on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 can be extended to a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathcal{Y}}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\widetilde{\ell}\|_{\mathcal{X}}=\|\ell\|_{\mathcal{Y}}$
\end_inset

.
 This is an immediate consequence of our more general version that we have
 just proved.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 be a nonzero vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\|\ell\|=1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{0})=\|x_{0}\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

So if you have two points 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, then there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a)\neq\ell(b)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a reflexive Banach space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 be a closed subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}\in\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{d}(x,\mathcal{Y})=\|x-y_{0}\|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We can replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

 with a convex set.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{Y}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(y)=\|y-x\|
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\mathcal{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Geometric Form of the Hahn-Banach Theorem 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gauge Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 A point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 is said to be an 
\series bold
interior point 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+ty\in S$
\end_inset

.
 We denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,S$
\end_inset

 to be the set of all interior points of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}\,S$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}\,S$
\end_inset

, then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0,0}>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon_{0,0}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0+t\cdot0\in S$
\end_inset

.
 The converse of course isn't true (take 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{0\}$
\end_inset

).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\backslash
label{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Here we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 to emphasize that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
depends 
\emph default
on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Usually we will just write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{x,y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an interior point.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)=\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)x\in C\}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 This is called the 
\series bold
gauge functional 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(V,\|\cdot\|)$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{B}_{1}[0]$
\end_inset

 be the closed unit ball centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 with radius 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)=\|x\|$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gauge Functional is a Partial-Seminorm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{propgaugefunctionalisquasiseminorm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an interior point.
 Then the gauge functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We first show 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is subadditive.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $a=\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

 and set 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)+\varepsilon/2$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/a)x,(1/b)x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex, we see that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{a+b}(x+y)=\frac{a}{a+b}\left(\frac{1}{a}x\right)+\frac{b}{a+b}\left(\frac{1}{b}y\right)\in C.
\]

\end_inset

It follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)+\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)+\varepsilon & =a+b\\
 & \geq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x+y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is subadditive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Next we show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 satisfies nonnegative homogeneity.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 First note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda=0$
\end_inset

, then since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(0) & =\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)\cdot0\in C\}=0,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

we have 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0\cdot\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)=\mathrm{p}_{C}(0\cdot x)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we may assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathrm{p}_{C}(\lambda x) & =\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)\lambda x\in C\}\\
 & =\lambda\inf\{\alpha>0\mid(1/\alpha)x\in C\}\\
 & =\lambda\mathrm{p}_{C}(x).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Finally note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is nonnegative by definition.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Properties of Gauge Functional
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be a convex set with 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 as an interior point.
 We have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\mathrm{p}_{C}\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,C=\{\mathrm{p}_{C}<1\}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 1.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/1)x\in C$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x+\varepsilon x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+\varepsilon x & =(1+\varepsilon)x\\
 & =\frac{1}{1/(1+\varepsilon)}x
\end{align*}

\end_inset

shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\leq1/(1+\varepsilon)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Conversely, let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha<1$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}(C)$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $ty\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x+(1-\alpha)ty & =\alpha(1/\alpha)x+(1-\alpha)ty\in C
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is convex.
 In particular, setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=(1-\alpha)\varepsilon$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $|t|<\delta$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x+ty\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Gauge Functional Induced from Partial-Seminorm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Proposition~(
\backslash
ref{propgaugefunctionalisquasiseminorm})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex subset of a real vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

, then the gauge functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a partial-seminorm.
 We will now show a converse to this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be a partial-seminorm, and set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\{p\leq1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set, and moreover, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}=p$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p((1-\alpha)x+\alpha y) & \leq p((1-\alpha)x)+p(\alpha y)\\
 & =(1-\alpha)p(x)+\alpha p(y)\\
 & \leq(1-\alpha)+\alpha\\
 & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

implies 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\alpha)x+\alpha y\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a convex set.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now assume there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})<p(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})\leq\alpha<p(x_{0})
\]

\end_inset

and such that 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $p((1/\alpha)x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)p(x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{0})\leq\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)\geq p(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Now assume there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x_{0})<\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(x_{0})\leq\alpha<\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)p(x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $p((1/\alpha)x_{0})\leq1$
\end_inset

 which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/\alpha)x_{0}\in C$
\end_inset

.
 This contradicts the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(x_{0})$
\end_inset

 is the infimum of all such 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $p(x)\geq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in V$
\end_inset

.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty convex subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $C=\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin C$
\end_inset

, there exists a hyperplane 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is some linear functional and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By translating if necessary, we may assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\mathrm{int}\,C$
\end_inset

.
 This means it is possible to define the gauge potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathbb{R}y\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(ay)=a$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $ay\in\mathbb{R}y$
\end_inset

.
 Notice if 
\begin_inset Formula $a<0$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(ay) & =a\\
 & <0\\
 & \leq\mathrm{p}_{C}(ay),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(ay) & =a\\
 & \leq a\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)\\
 & =\mathrm{p}_{C}(ay),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{p}_{C}(y)\geq1$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin\mathrm{int}\,C=C$
\end_inset

.
 So we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}|_{\mathbb{R}y}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore by the Hahn-Banach Theorem, we can extend 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}|_{\mathbb{R}y}=\ell$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widetilde{\ell}(x)\leq\mathrm{p}_{C}(x)<1.
\]

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\widetilde{\ell}<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
 Also clearly 
\begin_inset Formula $\widetilde{\ell}(y)=1$
\end_inset

, and so we are done.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
First Geometric Form of Hahn-Banach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (first geometric form of Hahn-Banach) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-vector space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq V$
\end_inset

 be nonempty convex sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathrm{int}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a hyperplane that separates 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, there exists a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell\geq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=A-B=\{a-b\mid a\in A,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a nonemtpy convex set.
 It's also easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{int}\,C=C$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\bigcup_{b\in B}A-\{b\}.
\]

\end_inset

Also 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin C$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint from one another.
 By the previous result, there exists a linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\{\ell=0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq\{\ell<0\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b\in C$
\end_inset

, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
0 & >\ell(a-b)\\
 & =\ell(a)-\ell(b),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a)<\ell(b)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}\leq\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}.
\]

\end_inset

So choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell\leq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell\geq\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Second Geometric Form of Hahn-Banach
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (second geometric form of Hahn-Banach) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be two nonempty convex sets such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is closed and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 Then there exists a closed hyperplane that strictly separates 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 More precisely, there exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon V\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $C=A-B=\{a-b\mid a\in A,b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 It's easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is a nonemtpy convex set.
 It's also easy to see that 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $0\notin C$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are disjoint from one another.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{c}$
\end_inset

 is open so there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $r>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\subseteq C^{c}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)\cap C=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 By the previous first geometric form of Hahn-Banach, we can separate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{B}_{r}(0)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 by a hyperplane, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\ell=\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(a-b)\leq\ell(rx)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)$
\end_inset

.
 It can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is bounded.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(a-b)\leq\inf\{\ell(rx)\mid x\in\mathrm{B}_{1}(0)\}=-r\|\ell\|.
\]

\end_inset

Now take 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=(1/2)r\|\ell\|>0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(a)+\varepsilon\leq\ell(b)-\varepsilon
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in B$
\end_inset

.
 This implies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}<\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}.
\]

\end_inset

So choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 strictly between 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup\{\ell(a)\mid a\in A\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf\{\ell(b)\mid b\in B\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lower Semicontinuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
lower semicontinuous 
\series default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi\leq c\}$
\end_inset

 is closed.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some basic facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 is a closed set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are lower semicontinuous implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}+\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of lower semicontinuous functions, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{i\in I}\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is also lower semicontinuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
if 
\begin_inset Formula $K\subseteq\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 is compact, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\inf_{x\in\mathcal{K}}\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

 is acheived.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Convexity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 be a normed linear space.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is said to be 
\series bold
convex 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(tx+(1-t)y)\leq t\varphi(x)+(1-t)\varphi(y)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some basic facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is convex if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 is a convex set in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 are convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}+\varphi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi_{i}\}_{i\in I}$
\end_inset

 are all convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{i\in I}\varphi_{i}$
\end_inset

 is convex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is convex, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\varphi\leq c\}$
\end_inset

 is a convex set for all 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 The converse is not true in general.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We usually assume both convexity and lower semicontinuity in optimization
 problems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 We define the 
\series bold
conjugate function 
\series default
of
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 
\series default
to be the function
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\colon\mathcal{X}^{*}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)=\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi(x))
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The conjugate function 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

 is sometimes called a 
\series bold
Fenchel transform 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 or a 
\series bold
Legendre transform 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\backslash
label{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(x)=\frac{1}{p}|x|^{p}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1<p<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}^{*}=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and one can show that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(x)=\frac{1}{q}|x|^{q}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $1<q<\infty$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $1/p+1/q=1$
\end_inset

.
 So Young's inequality, which says
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{a^{p}}{p}+\frac{b^{q}}{q}\geq ab
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\geq0$
\end_inset

 can be restated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(a)+\varphi^{*}(b)\geq ab.
\]

\end_inset

In general, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)+\varphi(x)\geq\ell(x).
\]

\end_inset

This is a simple consequence of the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}(\ell) & \geq\ell(x)-\varphi(x)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(\ell)+\varphi(x)\geq\ell(x)
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\backslash
label{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 be a lower semicontinuous convex function such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}<\varphi(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the normed linear space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and the subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\leq\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(x_{0},\lambda_{0})\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to show that both 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are nonempty, convex, closed sets.
 Furthemore, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is compact.
 By the second geometric form of Hahn-Banach, there exists a bounded linear
 functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\colon\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subseteq\{\ell>\alpha\}\quad\text{and}\quad B\subseteq\{\ell<\alpha\}.
\]

\end_inset

Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\colon\mathcal{X}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)=\ell(x,0)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 Then since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 is bounded, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 must be bounded too and it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is linear.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $k=\ell(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x,\lambda) & =\ell(x,0)+\ell(0,\lambda)\\
 & =\psi(x)+\lambda k.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now by we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
\ell(x,\lambda)>\alpha & \text{for }(x,\lambda)\in A\\
\ell(x_{0},\lambda_{0})<\alpha
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x)+\lambda k>\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\lambda)\in\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(x_{0})+\lambda_{0}k<\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 In particular, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(x)+\varphi(x)k>\alpha>\psi(x_{0})+\lambda_{0}k.
\]

\end_inset

This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{1}{k}\psi(x)-\varphi(x)<-\frac{\alpha}{k}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{*}(-1/k\psi)=\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(-(1/k)\psi(x)-\varphi(x))\leq-\frac{\alpha}{k}<\infty.
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\backslash
label{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is defined by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{**}(x)=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell)).
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Double Duality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\backslash
label{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Fenchel-Moreau) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\colon X\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 is lower semicontinuous, convex, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\neq\infty$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell)\leq\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi^{**}(x)=\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell))\leq\varphi(x).
\]

\end_inset

It remains to show 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}(x)\geq\varphi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 1: 
\series default
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\geq0$
\end_inset

 and assume for a contradiction that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}(x_{0})<\varphi(x_{0})$
\end_inset

.
 We apply the second geometric form of Hahn-Banach again in the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{X}\times\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 with sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)=\{(x,\lambda)\mid\varphi(x)\le\lambda\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{(x_{0},\varphi^{**}(x_{0}))\}$
\end_inset

.
 By the same argument as in the proof of the previous proposition, there
 exists a bounded linear functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(x)+k\lambda>\alpha\label{eq:firstineqfen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,\lambda)\in\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)=A$
\end_inset

 and such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(x_{0})+k\varphi^{**}(x_{0})<\alpha\label{eq:secondineqfen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that we could have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x_{0})=\infty$
\end_inset

, so we can't plug in 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{0},\varphi(x_{0}))$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:firstineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $k>0$
\end_inset

 as in the proof of the previous proposition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x'\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x')<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(x',\varphi(x'))\in\mathrm{epi}(\varphi)$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x')+k\varphi(x')>\alpha$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell(x')+k\lambda>\alpha\label{eq:thirdineqfen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\geq\varphi(x')$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0$
\end_inset

, then by taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to\infty$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:thirdineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty\geq\alpha$
\end_inset

 which is obviously impossible.
 So we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi\geq0$
\end_inset

, we have by 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:firstineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\ell(x)+(k+\varepsilon)\varphi(x) & \geq\ell(x)+k\varphi(x)>\alpha
\end{align*}

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathcal{X}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(x)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{*}\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell\right) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(-(k+\varepsilon)^{-1}\ell(x)-\varphi(x))\\
 & \leq-\frac{\alpha}{k+\varepsilon}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{**}(x_{0}) & \geq-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell(x_{0})-\varphi^{*}\left(-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell\right)\\
 & \geq-\frac{1}{k+\varepsilon}\ell(x_{0})+\frac{\alpha}{k+\varepsilon}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\ell(x_{0})+(k+\varepsilon)\varphi^{**}(x_{0})\geq\alpha
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

.
 Taking 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 gives us 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell(x_{0})+k\varphi^{**}(x_{0})\geq\alpha$
\end_inset

, which contradicts 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:secondineqfen})
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This contradiction proves that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}\geq\varphi$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Step 2: 
\series default
General case.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}\in\mathcal{X}^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0})<\infty$
\end_inset

 (such 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell_{0}$
\end_inset

 exists by the previous proposition).
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\colon\mathcal{X}\to(-\infty,\infty]$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(x)=\varphi(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is convex, lower semicontinuous, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\neq\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 So by step 1, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{1}^{**}=\varphi_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Now observe that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}^{*}(\ell) & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi_{1}(x))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}(\ell(x)-\varphi(x)+\ell_{0}(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\sup_{x\in\mathcal{X}}((\ell+\ell_{0})(x)-\varphi(x))-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0})\\
 & =\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})-\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Therefore
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi_{1}^{**}(x) & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi_{1}^{*}(\ell))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}(\ell(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\sup_{\ell+\ell_{0}\in\mathcal{X}^{*}}((\ell+\ell_{0})(x)-\varphi^{*}(\ell+\ell_{0})-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}))\\
 & =\varphi^{**}(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\varphi^{**}(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}) & =\varphi_{1}^{**}(x)\\
 & =\varphi_{1}(x)\\
 & =\varphi(x)-\ell_{0}(x)+\varphi^{*}(\ell_{0}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi^{**}=\varphi$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

